text = "	Cardinal: One last bird I need to tell you about for now is the cardinal. The cardinal is again a bit more complicated; it follows this condition:
[center](([b][color=green]C[/color][/b] [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color]) [color=orange]y[/color]) [color=orangered]z[/color] = ([color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color] [color=orangered]z[/color]) [color=orange]y[/color][/center]
	When [color=peru]C[/color] hears a bird [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color], it responds by calling out a new bird [color=peru]C[/color][color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color]. When [color=peru]C[/color][color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color] hears a bird [color=orange]y[/color], it responds with another new bird ([color=peru]C[/color][color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color])[color=orange]y[/color]. Finally when ([color=peru]C[/color][color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color])[color=orange]y[/color] hears [color=orangered]z[/color], it responds with what [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color][color=orangered]z[/color] would have said when hearing [color=orange]y[/color].

	Now that we know some birds we can start to learn about them. One interesting place to start is by trying to figure out what is [color=peru]C[/color]’s response to [color=peru]T[/color]. From what we have learned so far, there doesn't seem to be a rule telling us what this bird is. One way of finding out what bird it is, is by calling out the name of a new bird [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color] to it and seeing how it responds. When [color=peru]C[/color][color=peru]T[/color] hears [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color], it responds by "
